      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The critique that substantive due process allows judges to invent rights is a valid concern because it grants unelected judges immense power to rewrite the Constitution. This judicial activism allows the judiciary to impose a specific political agenda onto the law, bypassing the democratic process of elected representatives. When judges create rights not explicitly enumerated, they are essentially substituting their personal views for the will of the people. This undermines the principle of limited government that the Constitution was designed to uphold.",
      "source": "target",
